    "Evaluation": {
      "text": "",
      "subsections": {
        "Pediatric_Appendicitis_Score": {
          "text": "Score ≤ 2\nLow risk (0-2.5%)\nConsider discharge home with close follow up\nScore 3-6\nIndeterminate risk\nConsider serial exams, consultation, or imaging\nScore ≥ 7\nHigh risk\nConsider surgical consultation",
          "tables": [
            [
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "Anorexia",
                "+1": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "Migration of pain to RLQ",
                "+1": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "Fever",
                "+1": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "Cough/percussion/hopping tenderness",
                "+1": "+2"
              },
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "RLQ tenderness",
                "+1": "+2"
              },
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "Leucocytosis (WBC > 10,000)",
                "+1": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Nausea/vomiting": "Neutrophilia (ANC > 7,500)",
                "+1": "+1"
              }
            ]
          ]
        },
        "Pediatric_Appendicitis_Risk_Calculator_(pARC)": {
          "text": "pARC score shown to outperform Pediatric Appendicitis Score. pARC score accurately assesses risk of appendicitis in children age 5 years and older in community EDs\n[2]",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Alvarado_Clinical_Scoring_System": {
          "text": "Clinical scoring system, where a score (Total=10) is composed on presence/absence of 3 signs, 3 symptoms and 2 lab values to help guide in case management.\n≤3 = Appendicitis unlikely\n≥7 = Surgical consultation\n4-6 = Consider CT\nMANTRELS\nMnemonic:\nM\nigration to the right iliac fossa,\nA\nnorexia,\nN\nausea/Vomiting,\nT\nenderness in the right iliac fossa,\nR\nebound pain,\nE\nlevated temperature (fever),\nL\neukocytosis, and\nS\nhift of leukocytes to the left (factors listed in the same order as presented above).",
          "tables": [
            [
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Elevated Temperature (37.3°C or 99.1°F)",
                "+2": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Rebound Tenderness",
                "+2": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Migration of Pain to the Right Lower Quadrant",
                "+2": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Anorexia",
                "+2": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Nausea or Vomiting",
                "+2": "+1"
              },
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Leukocytosis > 10,000",
                "+2": "+2"
              },
              {
                "Right Lower Quadrant Tenderness": "Leukocyte Left Shift",
                "+2": "+1"
              }
            ]
          ]
        },
        "Laboratory_Findings": {
          "text": "Abdominal panel\nCBC\n<10K is a negative predictor of appendicitis\nHowever, normal WBC does not rule-out appendicitis\nChemistry\nConsider LFTs + lipase\nConsider coagulation studies (PT, PTT, INR), as a marker of liver function\nConsider urine pregnancy test (age appropriate)\nUrinalysis\n7-25% of patients with appendicitis have\nsterile pyuria\nConsider\nserum lactate",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Imaging": {
          "text": "Consider in intermediate or higher risk patients\nUltrasound\nSn: 88%, Sp: 94%\nConsider as 1st choice in non-obese children\nIndeterminate\nultrasound\nand an Alvarado <5 (see below) has an NPV of 99.6%\n[3]\nCT with IV contrast\nSn: 94%, Sp: 95%\nConsider if ultrasound is equivocal\nOR\nstrong suspicion despite normal ultrasound",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Diagnosis": {
          "text": "Patients can be ruled out via a combination of history, physical, labs, and imaging.\nConfirmatory diagnosis is typically made on imaging\nUltrasound is typically performed first:\nIf appendix is positive, appendicitis is ruled in\nIf appendix is visualized and negative, appendicitis is ruled out\nIf appendix is unable to be visualized (i.e., indeterminant), then post-test probability is unchanged. Re-examine and consider CT as next diagnostic study.",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
